  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Every time a suburb report, property data service, or agent presents a Brisbane price figure, the number quoted is almost always the median. Not the average, not the mean, the median. For most sellers that distinction passes without comment, but understanding exactly what each number represents, and where each one breaks down, is one of the more practically useful things a seller can know when interpreting market data and questioning their agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the median actually is</h2>
      <p>The median sale price for a suburb is the middle value when all sale prices for a given period are arranged from lowest to highest. If 11 homes sell in a suburb over a quarter, the median is the price of the sixth sale in that ranked list, with five sales below it and five above it. Exactly half of all sales occurred at or below the median price, and half occurred at or above it.</p>

      <p>It does not measure what a typical home sold for in any descriptive sense. It simply identifies the midpoint of the distribution. A suburb with a handful of entry-level units and several large family homes on big blocks will produce a median that accurately reflects neither type. The median is a statistical position, not a valuation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the average is, and why it is rarely used for property</h2>
      <p>The average, or mean, is the total of all sale prices divided by the number of sales. For most data sets this is a useful measure, but property is one of the contexts where it breaks down reliably. The reason is outliers. A single exceptional result at the top of the market, one $10 million sale in a suburb where most properties transact between $1 million and $2 million, will pull the average upward significantly while the median barely moves. The same distortion happens at the bottom of the market with distressed sales or properties in very poor condition.</p>

      <p>This is why analysts, agents, and property researchers default to the median when describing Brisbane market conditions. The median is resistant to outliers by construction. The average is not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the median does not tell you</h2>
      <p>The median tells you the midpoint of what actually sold. It does not tell you what your specific property is worth. This distinction matters more than most sellers initially appreciate.</p>

      <p>If a suburb median is $1.4 million, that number reflects the properties that changed hands over the measurement period. It does not reflect the mix of properties currently listed, the condition of those sales relative to yours, or whether the properties that sold were comparable to your home in any meaningful sense. A seller whose property is a well-presented four-bedroom home on a large block should not price off the suburb median if the recent sales driving that median included a mix of two-bedroom units, original 1960s homes, and properties sold under financial pressure.</p>

      <p>The median is also sensitive to the composition of what sells in a given period. If a significant number of units transact in one quarter and fewer houses sell, the median will drift downward without any actual change in house prices. This compositional shift is one of the less understood sources of apparent median volatility in mixed-stock suburbs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to use median data correctly as a seller</h2>
      <p>The most legitimate use of the median for a seller is tracking the direction of the market over time, not establishing a price for a specific property. A rising median across consecutive quarters is a reliable indicator of increasing buyer demand relative to supply in that suburb. A falling median indicates the reverse. This trend data is genuinely useful context.</p>

      <p>For the purpose of pricing your property, the median is too blunt. What you need instead is a set of comparable sales: properties that are genuinely similar to yours in type, size, condition, land area, and location within the suburb, that have sold within the past 60 to 90 days. Three to five strong comparables will give you a far more reliable basis for a price expectation than any median figure.</p>

      <p>Clearance rates and the median used together give a richer picture than either does in isolation. An auction clearance rate tells you what proportion of properties taken to auction sold under the hammer. A rising clearance rate indicates buyer conviction and competition. Combined with a rising median, it suggests the market is actively strengthening. A falling clearance rate alongside a flat or declining median tells you that buyers have more negotiating power and campaigns are taking longer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The right question to ask your agent</h2>
      <p>When an agent presents you with suburb price data, the most useful question you can ask is not what the suburb median is. It is: what have the three most comparable properties to mine actually sold for in the last 90 days? If your agent cannot answer that question with specific addresses, sale prices, and a brief commentary on how each property compares to yours, the median figure they have quoted you is not a useful basis for your decision.</p>

      <p>The median is a starting point for understanding a market, not a finishing point for pricing a property. The sellers who get the best results are the ones who understand the difference and ask the questions that get them to the more granular answer.</p>

